h4. Problem
On JIRA Agile enabled projects, the Project Summary screen is automatically redirected to Agile boards when the new project navigation is enabled. To access the summary page, users must click the project avatar icon on the left bar.

h4. Workaround
Disable the new project navigation and the summary page is no longer redirected. You can do this on [per-user|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/JIRA/Project+navigation+options] or a [global basis|https://confluence.atlassian.com/display/JIRA/Configuring+Project+Navigation].

or

# Access the Dark Features Administration screen via direct URL (_<INSTANCE_URL>/secure/admin/SiteDarkFeatures!default.jspa_)
# Disable dark feature {{com.atlassian.jira.projects.ProjectCentricNavigation.Switch}}
# Add dark feature {{com.atlassian.jira.projects.ProjectCentricNavigation.Disabled}}

h4. Suggestion
Give the option to users choose whether they want to automatically be redirected or not to the Agile boards.

Currently, {{GadgetProcessorImpl}} creates a new {{WebResourceAssembler}} for each occurrence of {{#includeResources()}} in the gadget specification; see method {{processIncludeResources}}. 

This means that even if a given resource has been included in an earlier batch using {{#includeResources()}}, it will also be included in any subsequent batch that references it, even indirectly (e.g., via a dependency of an explicitly required resource).

For example, suppose one tries:

{code:xml}
#requireContext("context_one")
#includeResources()
#requireContext("context_two")
#includeResources()
{code}

And both “context_one” and “context_two” contain resources that depend on jQuery, you’ll get two copies of jQuery loaded by the gadget, which leads to all sorts of trouble besides being inefficient.

(I’ve only checked the sources for JIRA 6.3.12, but from a comment in the code I suspect this has been happening for a good while, and it’s probably still going on in newer code.)

Having this work is necessary for gadgets that need a lot of resources to display, but only a few to start the initial REST request. If all of it is part of a single batch.js file there’s a significant delay before the browser can interpret the JS, which essentially prevents gadgets from doing their REST requests in parallel with other resource loading.

